566
00:21:55,840 --> 00:21:57,910
I predict their salary.

567
00:21:57,910 --> 00:21:59,680
Well, now what I
can do is I can say,

568
00:21:59,680 --> 00:22:01,060
well, I know what
the true salary

569
00:22:01,060 --> 00:22:02,840
was because it's labeled data.

570
00:22:02,840 --> 00:22:07,510
And so I'll compare the true
salary to the value I predicted.

571
00:22:07,510 --> 00:22:09,510
And what I'll actually
do is I'll just calculate

572
00:22:09,510 --> 00:22:11,040
the mean squared error, right.

573
00:22:11,040 --> 00:22:11,742
The difference.

574
00:22:11,742 --> 00:22:13,200
Think about it this
way, I can just

575
00:22:13,200 --> 00:22:16,110
subtract the true y
from the predicted y

576
00:22:16,110 --> 00:22:19,260
or vice versa, square those
so that the numbers are always

577
00:22:19,260 --> 00:22:23,610
positive, such that a bigger
number means that it's not

578
00:22:23,610 --> 00:22:24,910
as good of a predicted y.

579
00:22:24,910 --> 00:22:26,705
Because if the error
is smaller, that

580
00:22:26,705 --> 00:22:28,080
means even when
I square it, it's

581
00:22:28,080 --> 00:22:29,427
still relatively small number.

582
00:22:29,427 --> 00:22:30,760
That would be a good prediction.

583
00:22:30,760 --> 00:22:33,570
So we want to minimize the
distance between these true wise

584
00:22:33,570 --> 00:22:34,990
and predicted wise.

585
00:22:34,990 --> 00:22:36,880
But either way, I
make my prediction.

586
00:22:36,880 --> 00:22:38,615
I look at the error
between those two.

587
00:22:38,615 --> 00:22:40,240
That's what the loss
function is doing.

588
00:22:40,240 --> 00:22:42,340
The mean squared error
here is my loss function.

589
00:22:42,340 --> 00:22:44,340
And so if it's a big
mean squared error,

590
00:22:44,340 --> 00:22:45,520
that means it's a bad loss.

591
00:22:45,520 --> 00:22:46,452
My loss is large.

592
00:22:46,452 --> 00:22:47,910
If it's a small
mean squared error,

593
00:22:47,910 --> 00:22:50,710
that means it's a
small loss value.

594
00:22:50,710 --> 00:22:52,573
And my goal is to
minimize the loss.

595
00:22:52,573 --> 00:22:54,240
That's what I'm trying
to do is minimize

596
00:22:54,240 --> 00:22:56,160
the error in this model.

597
00:22:56,160 --> 00:22:57,990
And so that's what
the optimizer does,

598
00:22:57,990 --> 00:23:00,540
is the optimizer does a
little bit of calculus in here

599
00:23:00,540 --> 00:23:02,940
and it says, OK,
well, what direction

600
00:23:02,940 --> 00:23:04,680
do I need to move
all the weights

601
00:23:04,680 --> 00:23:07,000
in this model at the same time?

602
00:23:07,000 --> 00:23:09,385
How do I need to adjust
these numbers, these--

603
00:23:09,385 --> 00:23:12,100
I think about that, and that's
that y equals mx plus b.

604
00:23:12,100 --> 00:23:15,430
In what ways do I need to
adjust those m's and b's such

605
00:23:15,430 --> 00:23:18,460
that I reduce the distance
between the true y

606
00:23:18,460 --> 00:23:20,320
and the predicted y.

607
00:23:20,320 --> 00:23:21,830
And I only do a small step.

608
00:23:21,830 --> 00:23:24,470
I don't try to make this in
one jump in one training pass,

609
00:23:24,470 --> 00:23:25,510
I let this be iterative.

610
00:23:25,510 --> 00:23:27,490
So it just takes a little
step here each time.

611
00:23:27,490 --> 00:23:28,690
And then every time
through is trying

612
00:23:28,690 --> 00:23:30,350
to get better and
better and better.

613
00:23:30,350 --> 00:23:33,190
And so given enough data
and enough compute power,

614
00:23:33,190 --> 00:23:35,950
I should conceivably be able
to learn any sort of function,

615
00:23:35,950 --> 00:23:38,240
any mapping between
inputs X and Y's.

616
00:23:38,240 --> 00:23:41,630
It's just a matter of
data and compute power.

617
00:23:41,630 --> 00:23:44,090
And so that's basically
deep learning.

